aws::graph::propositions: # Meteorological Information and Flight Plan for Accident at BWI Airport
The accident site had Instrument Meteorological Conditions (IMC).
The accident occurred at night.
The observation facility was BWI airport.
BWI airport has an elevation of 143 feet above mean sea level.
The accident site was 0 Nautical Miles from BWI airport.
The observation time was 04:30 Local.
The direction from the accident site was 0 degrees.
The lowest cloud condition at the accident site was unknown.
The visibility at the accident site was 1.8 miles.
The lowest ceiling at the accident site was unknown.
The runway visual range (RVR) was 1600 feet.
Wind speed and gusts information was not provided.
No turbulence was forecasted or experienced.
Wind direction information was not provided.
Turbulence severity was not applicable for both forecast and actual conditions.
The altimeter setting was 29.18 inches of mercury.
The temperature was 7 degrees Celsius.
The dew point was 7 degrees Celsius.
Fog was in the vicinity of the accident site.
There was no precipitation at the accident site.
The flight departed from Newark, NJ (EWR).
The flight had filed an Instrument Flight Rules (IFR) flight plan.
The destination was Baltimore, MD (BWI).
The flight received an IFR clearance.
The departure time was 04:03 Local.
The accident occurred in Class B airspace.
